<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-709-720  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 709 720.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 25 1989 v6 n38 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CompuServe gateway provides subscribers with link to Internet.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   CompuServe Inc. (services).andO;Topic:     Computer bulletin boardsInformation and Referral ServicesConnectivityInternet (Computer network).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CompuServe Inc. last week officially unveiled a gateway designed to linksubscribers of its bulletin-board service with users of the nationwideInternet research-oriented network.andM;CompuServe subscribers can now exchange messages with users on any of themore than 1,000 independent government and academic networks that are part ofInternet, according to officials at CompuServe in Columbus, Ohio.andM;The gateway enables users of both networks to exchange messages in theformats with which they are familiar.andP;  Sending a message from CompuServe toInternet, for example, is as easy as sending a facsimile or telex messagefrom CompuServe, the officials said.andM;Internet users can send messages to the CompuServe network using formatssimilar to those that are standard to each of the independent networks withinthat system, they said.andM;Internet users can exchange messages with CompuServe users at no charge.andO;Subscribers to CompuServe must pay only the regular connect-time charges forthat network, company officials said.andM;Among the networks included as part of the Internet system are ARPAnet, theDefense Advanced Research Projects Agency network; NSFNet, a group of morethan 700 research and education networks; and NSNet, the National Aeronauticsand Space Agency network.andO;</TEXT></DOC>